> writes:
> >>my syllogism is of the form:
>>a is b.
>>c is a.
>>therefore c is b.
> >>this is a logically valid construction.
> >>your syllogism, however, is of the form:
>>a is b.
>>c is b.
>>therefore c is a.
> >>therefore yours is a logically invalid construction, >>and your comments don't apply. if all of those are "is"'s of identity, both syllogisms are valid.
if, however, b is a predicate, then the second syllogism is invalid.
(the first syllogism, as you have pointed out, is valid--whether b
is a predicate or designates an individual.) jim lippard dept. of philosophy university of arizona
